<h2>Expert Tips</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700">
  <li><strong class="text-wine-700">Match Wine Acidity to Seafood Preparation Method</strong> - The cooking technique dramatically changes your wine needs. Raw preparations like sashimi or crudo require wines with razor-sharp acidity like Albariño or Vermentino (pH 3.0-3.2) to cut through the fish's natural oils. Grilled or blackened seafood can handle fuller-bodied whites like aged Chardonnay or even light Pinot Noir, as the char and caramelization create flavor bridges that soften the wine's tannins.</li>

  <li><strong class="text-wine-700">Serve White Wines Colder Than Usual for Shellfish</strong> - When pairing with briny shellfish like oysters or clams, serve crisp whites at 42-45°F instead of the standard 50°F. This enhanced chill amplifies the wine's mineral backbone and salinity, creating a synergistic effect with the shellfish's oceanic character. Muscadet, Chablis, and Champagne particularly benefit from this temperature adjustment.</li>

  <li><strong class="text-wine-700">Choose Young Vintages for Delicate Fish</strong> - Sole, halibut, and other flaky white fish are easily overwhelmed by aged wines with developed tertiary aromas. Select wines within 2-3 years of vintage for these delicate preparations. The fresh primary fruit and mineral notes won't compete with subtle fish flavors, while older wines' honeyed, nutty characteristics can mask the seafood's natural sweetness.</li>

  <li><strong class="text-wine-700">Use Burgundy Glasses for Premium White Wine Pairings</strong> - The wider bowl of a Burgundy glass concentrates the aromatics of complex whites like aged Riesling or white Burgundy, essential when pairing with rich seafood dishes like lobster thermidor or pan-seared scallops. The enhanced nose amplifies the wine's ability to complement rather than compete with the dish's richness.</li>

  <li><strong class="text-wine-700">Consider Skin-Contact Wines for Meaty Fish</strong> - Orange wines and skin-contact whites like Friulano or Pinot Grigio offer the perfect bridge between white and red wine characteristics for substantial fish like tuna, swordfish, or monkfish. The extended skin contact provides just enough tannin structure (200-400mg/L) to stand up to these meatier textures without overwhelming their flavor.</li>

  <li><strong class="text-wine-700">Skip Decanting for Most Seafood Wines</strong> - Unlike red wine pairings, most seafood-friendly wines should go straight from bottle to glass. The delicate aromatics in young Sauvignon Blanc, Verdicchio, or rosé dissipate quickly when exposed to air. The exception is aged white Burgundy or Rhône whites, which benefit from 15-20 minutes of gentle aeration to open their complex mineral and floral notes.</li>

  <li><strong class="text-wine-700">Drink Immediately After Opening for Optimal Pairing</strong> - Seafood wines lose their critical freshness and salinity within 2-3 hours of opening, even with proper storage. Plan to consume the entire bottle during your seafood meal rather than saving it. The wine's ability to enhance the oceanic, mineral qualities of seafood diminishes rapidly as it oxidizes and warms.</li>

  <li><strong class="text-wine-700">Factor in Sauce Components, Not Just the Fish</strong> - The wine should complement the entire dish ecosystem. Butter sauces call for wines with natural richness like Chardonnay or Viognier, while tomato-based preparations need high-acid wines like Vermentino or Greco di Tufo to balance the sauce's acidity. Cream-based sauces require wines with enough body and acidity to cut through richness—think Chablis Premier Cru or aged Chenin Blanc.</li>
</ol>

  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between pairing wine with shellfish versus finfish?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Shellfish like oysters, mussels, and crab have higher salinity and mineral content, making them perfect for crisp, high-acid wines like Muscadet or Albariño that complement their briny sweetness. Finfish varies greatly—delicate white fish like sole pairs beautifully with light Sauvignon Blanc, while meatier fish like tuna or salmon can handle medium-bodied wines like Pinot Noir or even light Syrah.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I match wine to the seafood or the sauce when pairing?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Always match the wine to the dominant flavor, which is usually the sauce or preparation method. A delicate piece of halibut transforms completely with a rich butter sauce (pair with Chardonnay), spicy Cajun seasoning (try Riesling), or simple lemon and herbs (go with Sauvignon Blanc). The cooking method—grilled, poached, or fried—often influences the pairing more than the fish itself.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when choosing wine for seafood?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common error is assuming all seafood requires white wine, missing excellent opportunities with light reds and rosés. Grilled salmon, tuna steaks, or seafood in tomato-based sauces often pair better with Pinot Noir or Côtes de Provence rosé than with white wine. Another mistake is choosing wines that are too heavy or oaky, which can overpower delicate seafood flavors.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How do I choose wine for mixed seafood dishes like paella or cioppino?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">For complex seafood dishes with multiple types of fish and shellfish, focus on the cooking liquid and dominant seasonings. Spanish paella pairs excellently with Albariño or Verdejo, which complement both the saffron and variety of seafood. For tomato-based cioppino, choose a wine with good acidity like Sangiovese or Vermentino that can cut through the rich broth while enhancing all the different seafood components.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What are the best budget-friendly wines that pair well with most seafood?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Portuguese Vinho Verde offers exceptional value with its light, crisp character and natural effervescence that complements everything from grilled sardines to shellfish. Spanish Albariño from Rías Baixas provides mineral-driven complexity perfect for seafood at reasonable prices. For versatility, look for unoaked Chardonnay from regions like Chablis or Languedoc, which offer classic seafood-pairing qualities without premium pricing.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can sparkling wine work with seafood, and when should I choose it?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Sparkling wine is exceptional with seafood, especially fried preparations where the bubbles and acidity cut through oil and enhance delicate flavors. Champagne or Cava pairs beautifully with oysters, sushi, and seafood appetizers, while Prosecco complements lighter dishes like shrimp salad. The effervescence also makes sparkling wine ideal for seafood served as appetizers or in casual, celebratory settings.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What temperature should I serve wine when pairing with seafood?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Serve white wines slightly warmer than typical refrigerator temperature—around 45-50°F—to allow their aromatics to complement seafood without being too cold to taste. Light reds like Pinot Noir should be served slightly chilled at 55-60°F when pairing with meatier fish like salmon or tuna. Sparkling wines are best at 40-45°F to maintain their refreshing quality while enhancing the seafood's natural sweetness.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Are there any wines I should avoid completely with seafood?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Avoid heavily oaked, full-bodied red wines like Cabernet Sauvignon or Barolo, as their tannins can create an unpleasant metallic taste when combined with fish. Super-oaky Chardonnays can also overwhelm delicate seafood flavors with excessive vanilla and butter notes. High-alcohol wines (over 14%) tend to overpower subtle seafood dishes, though they might work with very rich, heavily sauced preparations.</p>
  </div>
